**Proposition 3.4.** *(i) The entangled two-qubit state* *ϱ*~*AB is compatible with a PT-moment vector* *p*~*(4) if and only if*

*F* ( *p*~2~, *p*~3~*) &lt; *p*~4~* F*+ ( *p*~2~, *p*~3~*)*, *~∀~*(*p*~2~, *p*~3~*)* ∈ *A*.

&gt; *(ii) The separable two-qubit state* *ϱ*~*AB is compatible with a PT-moment vector* *p*~*(4)~ *if and only if*

*F*− ( *p*~2~, *p*~3~*)* &lt; *p*~4~* F* ( *p*~2~, *p*~3~*)*, *~∀~*(*p*~2~, *p*~3~*)* ∈ *A*.

*Proof.* According to Theorem 3.2 , it is equivalent to proving any two-qubit state *ϱ*~*AB~ is entangled if and only if the following inequality holds: *p*~4~ &gt; *F* ( *p*~2~, *p*~3~*)*, where *F* ( *p*~2~, *p*~3~*)* := ^3*p*2^~2~*−6*p*2*+8*p*3*+1^~6~*. This follows directly from the fact that

det(*ϱ*~*AB~) = ^3*p*2^~2~*−6*p*2*+8*p*3*−6*p*4*+1^~4~*. (3.23)

It follows from \[0, 0\] that *ϱ*~*AB~ is entangled if and only if det(*ϱ*~*AB~) &lt; 0. It follows that 3*p*2^~2~*− 6*p*2*+ 8*p*3*− 6*p*4*+ 1 &lt; 0, and equivalently Eq. ( 3.22) holds. This completes the proof.

According to Proposition 3.4, we identify the dividing surface represented by *p*~4~ = *F* ( *p*~2~, *p*~3~*)* which separates the whole 3D region of all two-qubit states into two parts corresponding to separable states and entangled states respectively.

